Predicting Hotel Cancellations¶

Introduction:

This data set contains booking information from two different hotels, a resort hotel and a city hotel located in Portugal. The data includes information such as when the booking was made, the length of stay, the number of adults, children and/or babies, customer type, guest country of origin, average daily rate, and whether the booking was cancelled. All of the bookings were due to arrive between July 1, 2015 and August 31, 2017. The data set can be obtained at: https://www.kaggle.com/jessemostipak/hotel-booking-demand#

The goal is to accurately predict whether or not a hotel booking was cancelled based on the booking information provided. For the purposes of this project, no-shows are treated as cancellations. The below analysis includes some preliminary data exploration, and ultimately culminates with the construction and comparison of several classification models. Multinomial Naive Bayes, KNN, SVM, & Random Forest models are explored, utilizing individual grid searches to optimize/tune model hyperparameters. Finally, all four models are compared using ROC curves.

The variables is_canceled and is_repeated_guest are really categorical in nature but are represented as numeric values. The last column, reservation_status_date, is an ordinal attribute, but in most cases is identical to the arrival date (expressed as variables arrival_date_year, arrival_date_month, arrival_date_week_number, and arrival_date_day_of_month). Reservation_status also more or less mirrors the variable is_cancelled, and will therefore be dropped (along with reservation_status_date). There are 12 categorical variables and 20 numeric attributes.

Clean data:¶

Drop unnecessary variables:

  • Drop company variable (~ 94% of data missing for this column)
  • Drop reservation_status_date (essentially the same as the arrival date)
  • Drop reservation_status (nearly identical to is_cancelled)
In [6]:
data.drop(columns=['company', 'reservation_status_date', 'reservation_status'], inplace=True)

Replace missing values:

  • For missing children values, assume no children
  • For missing country, replace with "Unknown"
  • If travel agent is missing, replace with 0
In [7]:
null_replacements = {'children': 0.0, 'country': 'Unknown', 'agent': 0}

data = data.fillna(null_replacements)

Replace all meal values listed as 'Undefined' with 'SC':

In [8]:
data['meal'].replace('Undefined', 'SC', inplace=True)  # dataset detail mentions these are the same

Drop rows that have no guests (values of 0 adults, 0 children, and 0 babies listed):

  • Some rows have zero guests listed; drop these observations
In [9]:
no_guests = list(data.loc[data['adults']
                   + data['children']
                   + data['babies']==0].index)

data.drop(data.index[no_guests], inplace=True)

The above bar plots of the categorical variables show that the three summer months of August, July, and May had the highest number of hotel bookings. We can also see that most guests only had a breakfast (BB) meal type booked. The TA/TO distribution channel and Online TA market segment appear to be the most prevalent. Moreover, the most popular room type reserved (and assigned) was room A. Most guests did not provide a desposit and were labeled as transient (as opposed to contract or group) customer types. Furthermore, the classes of the target variable is_cancelled (used in the following classification modeling) do not appear to be too imbalanced.

Look at the percentage of cancellations per month for each hotel type (city & resort):

In [14]:
# resort hotel bookings and cancellations:
res_booked = data[(data['hotel'] == 'Resort Hotel')].groupby('arrival_date_month')['hotel'].count()
res_cancelled = data[(data['hotel'] == 'Resort Hotel')].groupby('arrival_date_month')['is_canceled'].sum()

res_cancelled_data = pd.DataFrame({'Hotel': 'Resort Hotel',
                                'Month': list(res_booked.index),
                                'Bookings': list(res_booked.values),
                                'Cancellations': list(res_cancelled.values)})

# city hotel bookings and cancellations:
city_booked = data[(data['hotel'] == 'City Hotel')].groupby('arrival_date_month')['hotel'].count()
city_cancelled = data[(data['hotel'] == 'City Hotel')].groupby('arrival_date_month')['is_canceled'].sum()

city_cancelled_data = pd.DataFrame({'Hotel': 'City Hotel',
                                'Month': list(city_booked.index),
                                'Bookings': list(city_booked.values),
                                'Cancellations': list(city_cancelled.values)})

# cancellation percentages:
full_cancelled_data = pd.concat([res_cancelled_data, city_cancelled_data], ignore_index=True)
full_cancelled_data['cancel_percent'] = full_cancelled_data['Cancellations'] / full_cancelled_data['Bookings'] * 100

# ordered months:
months_ordered = ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 
          'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sept', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']
full_cancelled_data['Month'] = pd.Categorical(full_cancelled_data['Month'], categories=months_ordered, ordered=True)

# plot:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
sns.barplot(x = 'Month', y = 'cancel_percent', hue = 'Hotel',
            hue_order = ['City Hotel', 'Resort Hotel'], data = full_cancelled_data)
plt.title('Cancellation Percentages per Month', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Month', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Percent Cancelled', fontsize=14)
plt.legend(loc= 'upper right')
plt.show()

The percentage of hotel bookings cancelled per month appears to be consistently higher for city hotels than resort hotels across all months. Moreover, the total percentage of hotel cancellations appears to be highest during the warmer months.

Modeling Prep & Data Transformation:¶

Manually convert categorical variables to numeric values:

In [15]:
hotel_num = {'Resort Hotel': 0, 'City Hotel': 1}
data = data.replace(hotel_num)

month_num = {'Jan': 1, 'Feb': 2, 'Mar': 3, 'Apr': 4, 'May': 5, 'Jun': 6, 'Jul': 7, 'Aug': 8, 'Sept': 9, 'Oct': 10, 'Nov': 11, 'Dec': 12}
data = data.replace(month_num)

meal_num = {'BB': 0, 'FB': 1, 'HB': 2, 'SC': 3}
data = data.replace(meal_num)

market_num = {'Air': 0, 'Corp': 1, 'Dir': 2, 'Undef': 3, 'Group': 4, 'GDS': 4, 'TA/TO': 5, 'Off TA/TO': 5, 'On TA': 6, 'Comp': 7}
data = data.replace(market_num)

deposit_num = {'No Deposit': 0, 'Non Refund': 1, 'Refundable': 2}
data = data.replace(deposit_num)

customer_num = {'Contract': 0, 'Group': 1, 'Transient': 2, 'Transient-Party': 3}
data = data.replace(customer_num)

# use ordinal encoder to convert variables reserved_room_type, assigned_room_type, and country (encode alphabetically)
ord_encoder = OrdinalEncoder()
data['reserved_room_type'] = ord_encoder.fit_transform(np.array(data['reserved_room_type']).reshape(-1,1))
data['assigned_room_type'] = ord_encoder.fit_transform(np.array(data['assigned_room_type']).reshape(-1,1))
data['country'] = ord_encoder.fit_transform(np.array(data['country']).reshape(-1,1))

Split data into training/test sets:

In [16]:
matrix = data.drop(['is_canceled'], axis=1)   # x-variable data
target = data['is_canceled']                  # y-variable data

# use stratified sampling to ensure a proportional ratio of each class is present in train/test sets
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(matrix, target, stratify = target, test_size=0.2, random_state=33)

Check target class value ratios in training and test sets:

target_train = y_train.apply(lambda x: True if x==1 else False)                          # train: select cancelled reservations as true

target_test = y_test.apply(lambda x: True if x==1 else False)                      # test: select cancelled reservations as true
target_perc_test = len(target_test[target_test==True].index) / y_test.shape[0]     # test: calculate % of cancelled reservations

print('Percent of Training Target Cancelled Reservations Class:',round(target_perc_train * 100, 2),'%')

2. Classification Modeling¶

Multinomial Naive Bayes:¶

Grid search to tune hyperparameters:

In [19]:
nb = MultinomialNB()
alphas = [0.0001, 0.001, 0.005, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3, 0.4]
parameters = {'alpha': alphas, 'fit_prior' : [True, False]}      # grid search parameters
gs = GridSearchCV(nb, parameters, verbose=1, cv=5)

Using optimal parameters (alpha = .0001 and fit_prior = True), apply model to test data:

In [22]:
nb = MultinomialNB(alpha=.0001, fit_prior=True)  # initialize classifier with smoothing parameter alpha = .0001  & allow it to learn prior class probabilities

nb.fit(x_train, y_train)                        # fit on training data

pred_test_target = nb.predict(x_test)           # predict classes of test set

print(classification_report(y_test, pred_test_target))  # print classification report

Visualize results with confusion matrix:

In [23]:
nbcm = confusion_matrix(y_test, pred_test_target)

ax= plt.subplot()

ax.xaxis.set_ticklabels(['not cancelled', 'cancelled']); ax.yaxis.set_ticklabels(['not cancelled', 'cancelled']);

Although the overall accuracy of this multinomial naive bayes classifier is only 75%, it has an extremely high precision (97%) with respect to the cancelled class. That is, it is not misclassifying a hotel reservation as cancelled very often. This is important because in order for the hospitality industry to presumably make use of classification models such as this, it would be beneficial to err on the side of caution when attempting to determine whether hotel reservations will ultimately be cancelled (in order to prevent overbookings).

However, the precision (78%) with respect to the cancelled class is worse. Although this model correctly predicted a higher total number of cancellations, it also misclassified more reservations as cancelled that were actually not cancelled.

pred_test_target = rf.predict(x_test)           # predict classes of test set

print(classification_report(y_test, pred_test_target))  # print classification report

The overall accuracy of this random forest classifier is 90%. This is a relatively high accuracy, which is better than the three prior models. The precision (89%) with respect to the cancelled class is better than the knn and svm classifiers, but still not as good as the first multinomial naive bayes classifier (which only classified a small number of bookings as cancelled). However, it is likely the best model, as it was able to correctly predict a large number of bookings as cancelled with a relatively high degree of precision.

The hospitality industry might want to adopt a model such as this over the first multinomial naive bayes classifier as part of their marketing strategy if pursuing a more aggressive approach (although doing so would probably also increase the risk of potential overbookings).

Compare all four models using ROC curves:¶

In [41]:
models = [
{
    'label': 'Multinomial NB',
    'model': MultinomialNB(alpha=.0001, fit_prior=True),
},
{
    'label': 'KNN',
    'model': neighbors.KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5),
},
{
    'label': 'SVM',
    'model': SVC(gamma='scale', C=250, kernel='rbf', class_weight='balanced', probability=True),
},
{
    'label': 'Random Forest',
    'model': ensemble.RandomForestClassifier(criterion='gini', min_samples_split=2, n_estimators=100),
}
]

# iterate through models list:
for m in models:
    model = m['model']                  # select model
    model.fit(x_train, y_train)         # train model
    y_pred = model.predict(x_test)      # predict test target
# compute false postive rate, and true positive rate:
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, model.predict_proba(x_test)[:,1])
# calculate AUC to display on the plot:
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, model.predict(x_test))
# plot the computed values:
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='%s ROC (area = %0.2f)' % (m['label'], auc))

# settings for plot: 
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],'k--',label='No Skill')
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate (1-Specificity)')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate (Sensitivity)')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic', fontsize=14)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')  # legend location
plt.show()                     # display

The above graph shows the performance for each of the four models (Multinomial Naive Bayes, KNN, SVM, & Random Forest) over a range of probability thresholds. The random forest classifier performed very well, with highest respective AUC (area under the curve). And although the multinomial naive bayes classifier has a relatively low AUC, as mentioned earlier this classifier displayed the highest precision with respect to the cancelled class.
